Background:
The Physarum polycephalum genomic DNA was extracted from axenic
haploid amoebal cells (strain LU352 developed in Jennifer Dee's
laboratory
column2: Leicester University). Cell culturing and DNA sampling

column1: was carried out by Gerard Pierron and Marianne Benard (Institut
Andre Lwoff
Total assembled sequence coverage of Roche 454 instrument reads
was 54.6X (fragments
190Mb. The combined sequence reads were assembled using the Newbler
software
assembled contigs were scaffolded using Bambus v2.3 (Pop et al

column2: and a transcriptome-guided scaffolding algorithm (X. Chen

column1: and L. Landweber
column2: Department of Ecology and Evolutionary Biology

column1: Princeton University). This draft assembly was referred to as
Physarum polycephalum 10.0. In this version the assembly has been
cleaned of contaminating contigs. All scaffolds of at least 200
bases were retained for submission to the public databases. The
assembly is made up of a total of 69
scaffold length of nearly 54kb (N50 contig length was 2.2kb).
The National Human Genome Research Institute (NHGRI)
Institutes of Health (NIH) have provided the Genome Institute at
Washington University School of Medicine funding for sequence and
characterization of the Physarum polycephalum genome. The
individual reads for this project are available from the NCBI trace
archive.
For questions regarding this Physarum polycephalum 10.0 assembly
please contact Patrick Minx
Medicine (pminx@genome.wustl.edu).

Background:
The Physarum polycephalum genomic DNA was extracted from axenic
haploid amoebal cells (strain LU352 developed in Jennifer Dee's
laboratory
column2: Leicester University). Cell culturing and DNA sampling

column1: was carried out by Gerard Pierron and Marianne Benard (Institut
Andre Lwoff
Total assembled sequence coverage of Roche 454 instrument reads
was 54.6X (fragments
190Mb. The combined sequence reads were assembled using the Newbler
software
assembled contigs were scaffolded using Bambus v2.3 (Pop et al

column2: and a transcriptome-guided scaffolding algorithm (X. Chen

column1: and L. Landweber
column2: Department of Ecology and Evolutionary Biology

column1: Princeton University). This draft assembly was referred to as
Physarum polycephalum 10.0. In this version the assembly has been
cleaned of contaminating contigs. All scaffolds of at least 200
bases were retained for submission to the public databases. The
assembly is made up of a total of 69
scaffold length of nearly 54kb (N50 contig length was 2.2kb).
The National Human Genome Research Institute (NHGRI)
Institutes of Health (NIH) have provided the Genome Institute at
Washington University School of Medicine funding for sequence and
characterization of the Physarum polycephalum genome. The
individual reads for this project are available from the NCBI trace
archive.
For questions regarding this Physarum polycephalum 10.0 assembly
please contact Patrick Minx
Medicine (pminx@genome.wustl.edu).

Background:
The Physarum polycephalum genomic DNA was extracted from axenic
haploid amoebal cells (strain LU352 developed in Jennifer Dee's
laboratory
column2: Leicester University). Cell culturing and DNA sampling

column1: was carried out by Gerard Pierron and Marianne Benard (Institut
Andre Lwoff
Total assembled sequence coverage of Roche 454 instrument reads
was 54.6X (fragments
190Mb. The combined sequence reads were assembled using the Newbler
software
assembled contigs were scaffolded using Bambus v2.3 (Pop et al

column2: and a transcriptome-guided scaffolding algorithm (X. Chen

column1: and L. Landweber
column2: Department of Ecology and Evolutionary Biology

column1: Princeton University). This draft assembly was referred to as
Physarum polycephalum 10.0. In this version the assembly has been
cleaned of contaminating contigs. All scaffolds of at least 200
bases were retained for submission to the public databases. The
assembly is made up of a total of 69
scaffold length of nearly 54kb (N50 contig length was 2.2kb).
The National Human Genome Research Institute (NHGRI)
Institutes of Health (NIH) have provided the Genome Institute at
Washington University School of Medicine funding for sequence and
characterization of the Physarum polycephalum genome. The
individual reads for this project are available from the NCBI trace
archive.

please contact Patrick Minx
Medicine (pminx@genome.wustl.edu).
